<HEADLINE>
<P>
CAPRIATI WILL ADD GRAF TO HER LIST IN TODAY'S FEATURE AT WIMBLEDON 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By THOMAS BONK 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WIMBLEDON, England 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Who is missing from this list? Martina Navratilova, Monica Seles, Gabriela 
Sabatini and Arantxa Sanchez Vicario. 
</P>
<P>
Did you say Steffi Graf? 
</P>
<P>
In a career that began in March, Jennifer Capriati has played all the 
top-ranked players except Graf, ranked No. 1, but all that changes today. 
</P>
<P>
Capriati, 14, and Graf, 21, punctuate a long day of heavyweight matches today 
at Wimbledon as the 106th All England Championships begin a second week. 
</P>
<P>
Graf, who flew to Hamburg, West Germany, Saturday night to see a doctor about a 
flareup of sinusitis, said she expects a good match. 
</P>
<P>
"It wasn't that I was really eager for it before, but now that it's happened, 
I'll enjoy it," Graf said. 
</P>
<P>
Possibly, but Graf's road to a third consecutive Wimbledon title does not look 
very easy. After Capriati, she could play Jana Novotna, Seles in the semifinals 
and Navratilova in the final. 
</P>
<P>
Navratilova's way seems much clearer: Judith Weisner, then possibly Katarina 
Maleeva and Gabriela Sabatini before meeting Graf in the final. 
</P>
<P>
Fifteen fourth-round matches are scheduled today as well as the completion of 
Ivan Lendl's third-round match with Bryan Shelton that was halted at dusk 
Friday tied one set apiece. 
</P>
<P>
The top men's matches include second-seeded Boris Becker against Pat Cash, 
third-seeded Stefan Edberg against No. 13 Michael Chang, seventh-seeded Brad 
Gilbert against David Wheaton, Guy Forget against Christian Bergstrom and Goran 
Ivanisevic against Mark Koevermans. THOMAS BONK 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
GRAF, STEFFI; CAPRIATI, JENNIFER; TENNIS PLAYERS; WIMBLEDON (TENNIS TOURNAMENT) 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA070290-0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 241824 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
July 2, 1990, Monday, Home Edition 
</P>
