<HEADLINE>
<P>
SERBIANS VOTE; COMMUNISTS TRY TO KEEP POWER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
BELGRADE, Yugoslavia 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Serbians cast ballots Sunday in a referendum called by the republic's ruling 
Communists, who are attempting to retain power by exploiting rising Serbian 
anger over ethnic Albanian separatism in Kosovo province. 
</P>
<P>
The referendum asks voters in Serbia, the largest of Yugoslavia's six 
republics, to approve a Communist political program that calls for the 
enactment of a new constitution before promised multi-party elections. 
</P>
<P>
The Communists have proposed a constitution that eliminates virtually all 
autonomy for Kosovo, where the 1.7-million-strong ethnic Albanian majority has 
called for independence. The Albanian demand has outraged the rest of Serbia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
